          "body": "Moses's response to Gad and Reuben's petition is not a counter-offer — it is a sermon (32:6-15). He reaches back to Kadesh-barnea and the spy crisis of Numbers 13-14 with explicit detail: the spies went, saw, discouraged, and the Lord's anger burned (32:8-10). Moses identifies the structural sin precisely: the fathers 'discouraged the sons of Israel so that they did not go into the land which the LORD had given them' (32:9). And he names the consequence: forty years of wandering until the faithless generation was consumed (32:13). The rhetorical force of the sermon is that Gad and Reuben are not doing something new — they are doing something old. The pattern of seeing good things and choosing them over God's forward call is generational, and it carries generational consequences. 'You have risen up in your fathers' place, a brood of sinful men' (32:14) is Moses at his most direct. He is not merely scolding; he is diagnosing."
